text: They fail to mention that at the time of the 1947 division, Palestine was inhabited by 80% Arabs and 20% settlers. Major Palestinian cities, such as Haifa, had an Arab population exceeding 90%. Under the new division, these areas were allocated to the newly established state of Israel. The reality is that Israel was allocated 52% of Palestine, while the Arab population, the majority, was given 48%. On the surface, this might seem like a fair division, but the truth is that hundreds of thousands of Palestinians were forced to leave their homes after the division . the Arab countries dident accept this division as well as the palestiniens.

author: @Abby_walks
text: I think that creating a homeland for Jews after the atrocities of the Holocaust during WW2 was in theory a good one. An idea that was well-intentioned. However, in tangible and practical terms Palestinians were displaced from their homes and have had to suffer in order to create this homeland. I'm not sure it was right to create suffering for one group of people in an attempt to to alleviate the suffering of another. It was well-intentioned I believe, but I do not understand how it was ever thought that it could work. Was there not even a consideration that it might cause resentment by the Palestinians? (I am NOT by the way, saying that extreme violence commiting war crimes or taking hostages  is the answer! I am in no way condoning violence or war of any kind). I am simply saying that it seems naive to think that it would not have caused problems between the Jewish people/ Israelis and The Muslim/ Palestinian people, to believe that everyone would just live in harmony...

For muslims, it is the place where Muhammad ascended to heaven. Back in the 19th century when politics and religion were very intertwined, leaders made political decisions from religious standpoints, leading to this conflict in the first place. Understanding the religious emotions of the conflict is step one.

author: @rirkkadunz9453
text: Hi Then & Now,  a note on your subtitles:  it's great that you're doing the extra work to put timestamped subtitles in rather than relying solely on youtube's auto subtitles, but i think these subtitles would be worth an extra layer of double checking - i have seen a number of errors between the spoken word and the written text  (e.g. subtitles saying 1970 when you say 1917, among a few others).  I am guessing from the content of the subtitles that you have copied the contents of youtube's auto subtitles into your own submitted subtitles.  I think this is fine as a first step (because it removes a lot of the time-wasting work from subtitling), but if possible, it would be really special and appreciated if you were able to do a second pass over the subtitles you submit just to eliminate obvious errors in the algorithm's mishearing.  I know this is another layer of labour on top of the already labour intensive endevour of creating a video with the level of rigour which i have come to appreciate from your work, but it really does pay dividends for those who are watching without sound as well as those of us who like to watch using youtube's auto-translate feature (i personally like to watch and download the auto-translated subtitles for the languages that i'm learning so that i can get engaging content in my target languages that i can have some sort of faith in, though i know the auto-translate is fraught - it is at least a good starting point if i trust the english subtitles).

text:
Asking a country/region of people who have only if not almost entirely ever lived in an apartheid state to "respond appropriately" is fucking insane. The fact that anyone who supports Palestine has to say "but not Hamas" but not a single person who supports Israel has to say "but I don't support the Apartheid state" really says all that needs to be said about the rhetoric around this situation (at least here in the states).
The average age is so young mostly because all of the able bodied adults have already been killed or imprisoned and people still cannot understand how a percentage of these people end up radicalized, not saying I like or support it at all, just saying it logically checks out. Like Hasan is saying, somewhat of an inevitability because we should never expect a people to just sit a die slowly and the global expectation for them to do so is absolutely sickening.
Like what is the "Ethical Warfare Response"? I can't think of anything that wouldn't be violent, wouldn't result in death, wouldn't ultimately be a tragic event but the current alternative is literally letting warcrimes continue to happen and watch a people be genocided, and I THOUGHT we all agreed that those things are literally crimes against humanity.

author: @nitaybarshack6698
text:
1. Before Israel, there was a British mandate, not a Palestinian state

2. Before the British Mandate, there was the Ottoman Empire, not a Palestinian state.

3. Before the Ottoman Empire, there was the Islamic state of the Mamluks of Egypt, not a Palestinian state.

4. Before the Islamic state of the Mamluks of Egypt, there was the Ayubid Arab-Kurdish Empire, not a Palestinian state.

5. Before the Ayubid Empire, there was the Frankish and Christian Kingdom of Jerusalem, not a Palestinian state.

6. Before the Kingdom of Jerusalem, there was the Umayyad and Fatimid empires, not a Palestinian state.

7. Before the Umayyad and Fatimid empires, there was the Byzantine empire, not a Palestinian state.

8. Before the Byzantine Empire, there were the Sassanids, not a Palestinian state.

9. Before the Sassanid Empire, there was the Byzantine Empire, not a Palestinian state.

10. Before the Byzantine Empire, there was the Roman Empire, not a Palestinian

state.

11. Before the Roman Empire, there was the Hasmonean state, not a Palestinian state.
12. Before the Hasmonean state, there was the Seleucid, not a Palestinian state.

13. Before the Seleucid empire, there was the empire of Alexander the Great, not a Palestinian state.

14. Before the empire of Alexander the Great, there was the Persian empire, not a Palestinian state.

15. Before the Persian Empire, there was the Babylonian Empire, not a Palestinian state.

16. Before the Babylonian Empire, there were the Kingdoms of Israel and Judah, not a Palestinian state.

17. Before the Kingdoms of Israel and Judah, there was the Kingdom of Israel, not a Palestinian state.

18. Before the kingdom of Israel, there was the theocracy of the twelve tribes of Israel, not a Palestinian state.

19. Before the theocracy of the twelve tribes of Israel, there was an agglomeration of independent Canaanite city-kingdoms, not a Palestinian state

author: @acelovesit
text:
I came off Twitter because it was impossible to speak of diplomacy, it was impossible to speak of being able to condemn Hamas and the Israeli government. I love to read and listen about history, I enjoy reading about diplomacy, but even educating myself and offering to educate others just turns into one side vs another - which is anything but diplomatic. I get the anger on both sides, I get the history and I'm willing to understand that It's a serious and very complex issue, I just wish there were more people willing to understand and learn from the past and learn from diplomats from the UN.

The humanitarian issues should be the biggest focal point, innocent people always die by those in power who don't really care about them, only their own prejudices. One side you have Hamas being extreme to do the unimaginable, the other is and Israeli government going further beyond the two party state, and now collective punishment and mass murder. in the middle are innocent Israelis and Palestinians just trying to survive. It's so extreme, I just don't know if there are any solutions. I hope that there are those willing to stand up and fight for an equal society, not the destruction of one, or worse both.

I got banned from the UKPolitics subreddit for talking about diplomacy and talking about how its important that language is vital when peace-making, It's what I've learned from reading UN articles and about how language is a key element to bring back some sort of justice and understanding. I hope I don't get banned her, I just feel it's so important to speak about, that not many people are willing, or able, to do.

It covers the pre- and post-history of the 1948 Palestinian exodus, known as the Nakba or "catastrophe," and the ongoing conflict, drawing on the narratives of intellectuals, historians, eye-witnesses, and recently released archival documents and materials. The series is available to watch on Al Jazeera's website and was originally broadcast on Al Jazeera Arabic. author: @arthurluisaustrio
text:
In reality, it is difficult to assign blame to any single people. The conflict between Palestine and Israel is primarily a territorial dispute rather than a religious one. This is because most of that region was Arab and Palestinian, but British rule prevented the creation of a Palestinian state.
According to the Bible, this land should belong to both peoples, since it was promised to the descendants of Abraham(which includes both Arabs and Jews).

Edit: On second thought, there are many descendants of Isaac scattered around the world, especially in Arab countries. Many of Abrahamâ€™s descendants went to Arab lands and had children, and although those children were Arabs, they were still descendants of Isaac. In fact, there are probably many descendants of Isaac in Brazil or even throughout the world.
Therefore, the land should belong to various peoples, not only to the Jews, since God said it was for the descendants of Isaac â€” most of whom are Jews, but also people from other regions, such as Arab countries. Perhaps someone in these comments is a descendant of Isaac and doesnâ€™t even know it.


1. Husseinâ€“McMahon Correspondence (1915â€“1916)



A series of letters exchanged between Hussein bin Ali, Sharif of Mecca, and Sir Henry McMahon, the British High Commissioner in Egypt.

The British promised to support the creation of an independent Arab state (which, according to the Arab interpretation, included Palestine) in exchange for an Arab revolt against the Ottoman Empire.

2. Sykesâ€“Picot Agreement (1916)



A secret agreement between the United Kingdom and France (with Russian approval).

Divided the Middle East into zones of control and influence:

Blue Zone (France): northern Syria and Lebanon.

Blue Zone A (French influence): part of northern Palestine (Galilee region).

Red Zone (United Kingdom): areas of Iraq and southern Palestine.

The remainder of Palestine would be placed under international administration.

3. Balfour Declaration (1917)



A letter from British Foreign Secretary Arthur Balfour to Lord Rothschild.

Declared British support for the establishment of â€œa national home for the Jewish peopleâ€ in Palestine, provided that the civil and religious rights of existing non-Jewish communities were not harmed.

text:
The genocide in Gaza didnâ€™t start on Oct 7. It began in 1948 with the Nakba â€” when 750,000 Palestinians were expelled and 500 villages destroyed. What we see today is the continuation of 76 years of occupation, dispossession, ethnic cleansing, and genocide. What we are witnessing today is not an isolated war â€” itâ€™s the continuation of settler colonialism and ethnic cleansing that started in 1948:
1948 (Nakba): Mass expulsions, massacres, destruction of homes.
1967 (Naksa): More land occupied (West Bank, Gaza, East Jerusalem).
Ongoing: Siege on Gaza, illegal settlements, targeting of civilians, destruction of infrastructure, denial of basic human rights.
So when people say it â€œstarted on Oct 7,â€ they erase the decades of suffering and resistance of Palestinians. The genocide is not new â€” itâ€™s part of a 76-year-long project.

author: @Abby_walks
text: I think that creating a homeland for Jews after the atrocities of the Holocaust during WW2 was in theory a good one. An idea that was well-intentioned. However, in tangible and practical terms Palestinians were displaced from their homes and have had to suffer in order to create this homeland. I'm not sure it was right to create suffering for one group of people in an attempt to to alleviate the suffering of another. It was well-intentioned I believe, but I do not understand how it was ever thought that it could work. Was there not even a consideration that it might cause resentment by the Palestinians? (I am NOT by the way, saying that extreme violence commiting war crimes or taking hostages  is the answer! I am in no way condoning violence or war of any kind). I am simply saying that it seems naive to think that it would not have caused problems between the Jewish people/ Israelis and The Muslim/ Palestinian people, to believe that everyone would just live in harmony...

For muslims, it is the place where Muhammad ascended to heaven. Understanding the religious emotions of the conflict is step one.

author: @80sboi79
text:
No, Israel did not found Hamas. Hamas (Islamic Terrorist Organisation) was officially founded in 1987 during the First Intifada and emerged from the Palestinian Muslim Brotherhood. It was founded by Palestinian activists such as Sheikh Ahmed Yassin and others who belonged to the Muslim Brotherhood.

What is sometimes implied is that Israel may have tolerated or even indirectly favoured the Muslim Brotherhood in the 1980s as a religious alternative to the secular PLO (Palestine Liberation Organisation). However, this is not the same as Hamas being founded directly by Israel, and this interpretation is wrong.

Hamas developed into a militant organisation with the declared aim of completely wiping out Israel (From the river to the sea, which is a call for genocide) and murdering all Jews worldwide, which was clearly not in Israel's interests.
